Pull Request: https://github.com/wger-project/react/pull/1121
Problem: On the routine page, as the viewport narrows the exercise thumbnail drifted and visually obscured the text.Actual development process: Identified that the left "thumbnail column" was allowed to shrink/reflow under flex wrapping, while the right "text column" resisted shrinking due to min-content behavior. Updated the row to a non-wrapping layout so image and text stay aligned; fixed a non-shrinking width for the thumbnail column; allowed the text column to wrap within its own area; and stacked multiple thumbnails vertically with a small, consistent gap. Validated across common breakpoints and on mobile to ensure no overlap and stable rhythm.Maintainer interaction: Submitted targeted layout changes with screenshot; Author did a quick review.Outcome: Merged - pending next production deploy (not live yet).3. Lessons LearnedSubmit changes to the right repository - The workout ordering fix was initially applied to the compiled JavaScript bundle. Maintainers rightly rejected it and clarified that all React changes must be proposed in the wger-react repository. This experience highlighted the importance of understanding build pipelines before submitting patches.Design communication matters - For the calorie automation feature, presenting a bilingual, structured plan made it easier for maintainers to give feedback. Even though the feature is still under development, aligning ideas early prevented significant rework.Incremental wins build trust - Bai Lu's UI improvements show that even when initial attempts are not merged (PR #1105), the effort demonstrates competence and helps maintainers understand the contributor's intentions for subsequent PRs.Testing and reproducibility go hand-in-hand - For front-end layout fixes (language dropdown, routine thumbnails), attaching screenshots and responsive design notes reduced ambiguity and built reviewer confidence without requiring them to reproduce the environment manually.
